    <p style="color:#666;margin-bottom:2rem;">Updated: March 9, 2026 · 7 min read</p>

    <p>Pakistan's electricity tariff system operates on a progressive slab structure — the more you consume, the higher your per-unit rate. NEPRA (National Electric Power Regulatory Authority) sets uniform tariffs for all WAPDA DISCOs (LESCO, MEPCO, GEPCO, FESCO, IESCO, PESCO, HESCO, SEPCO, QESCO, TESCO, AJK). K-Electric has separate tariff rates set independently by NEPRA.</p>

    <h2>Protected vs Unprotected — The Most Important Distinction</h2>
    <p>The single most important thing to understand about Pakistan's electricity tariff is the <strong>Protected / Unprotected classification</strong>. Your classification determines which rate slab applies to you:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Protected Consumer (A-1 tariff):</strong> A domestic consumer whose average monthly consumption over the preceding 6 months is 200 units or less. Protected consumers pay subsidized rates starting at Rs 13.48/unit.</li>
      <li><strong>Unprotected Consumer (A-2 tariff):</strong> A domestic consumer whose average monthly consumption exceeds 200 units in any 6-month rolling window. Unprotected consumers face significantly higher rates starting at Rs 23.59/unit.</li>
    </ul>
    <div style="background:#fff3cd;border-left:4px solid #ffc107;padding:1rem 1.5rem;border-radius:4px;margin:1rem 0;">
      <strong>⚠️ Warning:</strong> If you cross 200 units in even a single month of summer (due to AC), your DISCO may reclassify you as Unprotected for the next 6 months — dramatically increasing your bills.
    </div>

